<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-01-03T13:40:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-01-03T13:40:00-05:00" n="7" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d7">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">839.00/2453: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Dominican Republic</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Herod</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Santo
                                        Domingo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-01-03T14:00:00-04:40"><hi rend="italic">January 3,
                                        1922—2 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received January 4—11:12
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>1. The Military Governor<note n="2" xml:id="d7fn2">Rear Admiral S. S.
                                Robison.</note> sailed today for Washington with Commander Rose,
                            Minister of Commerce. Last week the Admiral conferred with Jacinto de
                            Castro, Federico Velasquez, Francisco Peynado, and Enrique Jimenez to
                            (obtain?) agreement on plans of withdrawal and of warrant for Guardia
                            [National]. This conference proved fruitless.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Herod</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>